e Bible Today October 24, 1976 -- tThat You Might Have Life January 23, 1977 -- tNot to Condemn Us April 17, 1977 -- tThe Enigmatic God November 20, 1977 -- tRighteous Anger August 27, 1978 -- tThe Gothic Principle January 21, 1979 -- tSeeing and Not Seeing October 21, 1979 -- tHave You Been to Damascus? March 20, 1983 -- tThe Usefulness of a Useless Vision November 6, 1983 -- tThere Is a Point in Living November 13, 1983 -- tThe ‘‘Ah’’ ofWonder September 30, 1984 -- tMainline Churches February 10, 1985 -- tSlogans—And Hurts Underneath February 16, 1985 -- tChristmas Party December 15, 1985 -- tIt Matters Greatly February 23, 1986 -- tJesus’ Final Exam November 9, 1986 -- tGod under Pressure March 8, 1987 -- tWhen the Cross Lays Hold on You September 18, 1988 -- tNovember 5, 1989 -- tI Have Seen the Future November 15, 1992 -- tChildren of the Kingdom February 13, 1994 -- tStorm at Sea June 19, 1994 -- tAn Impossible Ethic February 19, 1995 -- tA Chief Text of the Church April 23, 1995 -- tA Sermon at Duke University October 15, 1995 -- tAwaiting New Wine February 27, 2000 -- tWe Do See Jesus October 8, 2000 -- tStargazers January 5, 2003 -- tThe Enemy Lines Are Hard to Find March 16, 2003 -- tThe Snake Savior March 30, 2003 -- tThe Best-Kept Secret in the Bible June 8, 2003 -- tConfused, yet Curious, about Jesus August 31, 2003 -- tIndex to Scripture0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMany of America’s greatest Protestant preachers—Paul Tillich, William Sloane Coffin, Barbara Brown Taylor, Fleming Rutledge, Peter J. Gomes, Billy Graham, and others—have spoken powerfully from the pulpit of the “great towering church” that is the spiritual and architectural center of Duke University. This collection of fifty-eight of the most notable sermons proclaimed from that pulpit commemorates the seventy-fifth anniversary of the groundbreaking for Duke Chapel. It is a sweeping panorama of sermons selected and edited by Bishop William H. Willimon, Dean of the Chapel for twenty years and one of the most widely read writers on preaching in America.Opening with the sermon preached in June 1935 at the dedication of the Chapel and closing with one by Willimon delivered at the beginning of the 2003–4 school year, this volume presents Protestant Christianity at its most eloquent and prophetic. Some sermons are pure meditations on biblical texts; others are period pieces in the best sense of the term, reflecting on such contemporary concerns as civil rights, the assassinations of Martin Luther King Jr. and Robert F. Kennedy, and the wars in Europe, Vietnam, and Iraq. Willimon provides a brief introduction to each sermon, commenting on the work and thought of the preacher. Diverse in subject and style, the sermons collected in this volume are a treasure for those who love fine preaching, a resource for those studying the history of homiletics, and a light to rekindle the memories of those who have worshiped in the Chapel over the years.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aSermons, Americany20th century. 0aUniversities and collegesvSermons. 7aRELIGION / Sermons / Christian.2bisacsh1 aAchtemeier, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAugsburger, Myron S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarr, Browne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeach, Waldo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBethge, Eberhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlake, Eugene Carson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrueggemann, Walter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButtrick, Dav